:QUOTE
A speaker you built costs less and sounds better than one a factory built at the same price. The math works.

:INFO
Why DIY Speakers Sound Better Per Dollar
Commercial speaker manufacturing bundles materials, labor, retail markup, and marketing into the price. A DIY kit from a reputable designer (Dayton Audio, CSS Audio, GR Research) puts the same budget directly into drivers, crossover components, and cabinet materials. The crossover is designed around measured driver response — not approximated for cost reduction. Typical result: DIY speakers outperform commercial speakers costing 3 to 5 times more.

:COUNTER.half
Kit Cost
$150 to $400 for a well-designed stereo pair including cabinet
|
:COUNTER.half
Crossover Frequency
Where the tweeter takes over from the woofer — set by the designer

:PATH
Choose a Kit and Study the Plans
Read the entire design documentation before ordering parts.
|
:INFO
Choose a Kit and Study the Plans
Buy a kit with full design documentation — driver specs, crossover schematic, cabinet dimensions with bracing details, and a measurement set showing predicted frequency response. Dayton Audio Overnight Sensations and the GR Research NX-Studio are popular entry-level designs. Read the entire instruction set before cutting or ordering. Cabinet tolerance is critical: +/- 1mm on internal volume changes bass response.

:PATH
Cut and Assemble the Cabinet
Cut MDF or plywood to exact dimensions and glue up the enclosure.
|
:INFO
Cut and Assemble the Cabinet
Use 3/4-inch MDF for cabinet panels. Cut to the dimensions in the plans — a table saw produces the straightest cuts. Apply PVA wood glue to all mating edges and clamp firmly. Use corner clamps or a band clamp for square assemblies. Line interior walls with acoustic damping material (fiberglass, acoustic foam, or long-fiber wool) as specified in the plans.

:PATH
Solder the Crossover
Solder inductors, capacitors, and resistors per the schematic.
|
:INFO
Solder the Crossover
The passive crossover is a network of inductors (air-core coils), capacitors, and resistors that routes frequencies to the correct driver. Solder on a piece of perfboard or mount on terminal strips per the plans. Use rosin-core solder. Air-core inductors must be oriented 90 degrees apart to prevent coupling. Test continuity on each branch before installation.

:PATH
Install Drivers and Wire
Mount the woofer and tweeter, connect to the crossover, and test.
|
:INFO
Install Drivers and Wire
Install a gasket or foam seal around each driver cutout to prevent air leakage around the frame. Mount drivers with machine screws (not wood screws — they strip). Connect woofer and tweeter to the crossover per polarity markings in the plans. Incorrect polarity creates a cancellation null at the crossover frequency. Test with a battery before final installation: positive terminal to positive driver should move the woofer cone forward.

:CHECKLIST
Tools Required
[ ] Table saw or circular saw for panel cutting
[ ] Bar or pipe clamps for cabinet assembly
[ ] Soldering iron and solder for crossover
[ ] Router for driver cutouts (or carefully with a jigsaw)
[ ] Multimeter for continuity testing
[ ] Sandpaper through 180-grit for cabinet finishing

:NOTE
Cabinet Volume Must Be Exact
The port length and cabinet volume are calculated for the specific drivers in the kit. Building a cabinet smaller than designed raises the system resonance and reduces bass extension. Larger reduces sensitivity and potentially causes port noise. Follow the plans exactly — this is not a dimension that benefits from improvisation.

:QUOTE
You built the thing your ears trust. That is a different relationship than buying it.

